To find out the total time it takes for Carla to download the 200 GB file, we need to calculate the time taken for the first download (interrupted by Windows update) and the time taken for the restart.

**Step 1: Calculate the time taken for the first download.**

Carla's normal speed is 2 GB/minute, which means she would normally take:
\begin{equation*}
    200 \text{ GB} \cdot \frac{1 \text{ minute}}{2 \text{ GB}} = 100 \text{ minutes} \, .
\end{equation*}

She only manages to download 40% of the file before the interruption, which is:
\begin{equation*}
    0.4 \text{ x } 200 \text{ GB} = 80 \text{ GB}\, .
\end{equation*}

At 2 GB/minute, it took her 40 minutes to download 80 GB, i.e., the same amount of time it would take for her to download 40% of the entire 200 GB file.

**Step 2: Calculate the time taken for the restart**

20 minutes

**Step 3: Calculate the total time taken for the entire download.**

The total time taken, i.e., the time taken to download the initial 40% of the file, plus the Windows update, plus the restart of the download, is equal to:

(Time taken to download 40% of the file) + (20-minute update) + (time taken to restart the entire download)

\begin{equation*}
       (40 \text{ minutes}) + 20 \text{ minutes} + (100 \text{ minutes}) = \boxed{160 \text{ minutes}}.
\end{equation*}

So, the time taken for the entire download process is 160 minutes.

